#: ../../C/coefficient-of-X.rst:5
msgid "coefficient of X"
msgstr "coefficient of X"

#: ../../C/coefficient-of-X.rst:7
msgid "n\\."
msgstr "名詞"

#: ../../C/coefficient-of-X.rst:9
msgid ""
"Hackish speech makes heavy use of pseudo-mathematical metaphors. Four "
"particularly important ones involve the terms coefficient, factor, index of "
"X, and quotient. They are often loosely applied to things you cannot really "
"be quantitative about, but there are subtle distinctions among them that "
"convey information about the way the speaker mentally models whatever he or "
"she is describing. Foo factor and foo quotient tend to describe something "
"for which the issue is one of presence or absence. The canonical example is "
":ref:`fudge-factor`\\. It's not important how much you're fudging; the term "
"simply acknowledges that some fudging is needed. You might talk of liking a "
"movie for its silliness factor. Quotient tends to imply that the property is"
" a ratio of two opposing factors: \"I would have won except for my luck "
"quotient.\" This could also be \"I would have won except for the luck "
"factor\", but using *quotient* emphasizes that it was bad luck overpowering "
"good luck (or someone else's good luck overpowering your own). Foo index and"
" coefficient of foo both tend to imply that foo is, if not strictly "
"measurable, at least something that can be larger or smaller. Thus, you "
"might refer to a paper or person as having a high bogosity index, whereas "
"you would be less likely to speak of a high bogosity factor. Foo index "
"suggests that foo is a condensation of many quantities, as in the mundane "
"cost-of-living index; coefficient of foo suggests that foo is a fundamental "
"quantity, as in a coefficient of friction. The choice between these terms is"
" often one of personal preference; e.g., some people might feel that "
"bogosity is a fundamental attribute and thus say coefficient of bogosity, "
"whereas others might feel it is a combination of factors and thus say "
"bogosity index."
msgstr ""
"ハッカー流の話し方は、疑似数学的な比喩を多用します。特に重要な4つは、coefficient(係数)、factor(因子)、index of "
"X(Xの指数)、quotient(商)という用語を含みます。これらはしばしば、本当には定量化できないものにいい加減に適用されますが、それらの間には、話者が記述している対象を心の中でどうモデル化しているかについての情報を伝える微妙な区別があります。foo"
" factorとfoo quotientは、問題が存在か不在かであるものを記述する傾向があります。正準的な例は\\ :ref:`fudge-"
"factor`\\ "
"です。どれだけごまかしているかは重要ではなく、この用語は単に何らかのごまかしが必要であることを認めるだけです。映画をそのsilliness "
"factor(ばかばかしさ因子)ゆえに好きだと言うかもしれません。quotientは、その性質が対立する2つの因子の比であることを含意する傾向があります。「運の商がなければ勝てたのに」。これは「運の因子がなければ勝てたのに」とも言えますが、\\"
" *quotient*\\ を使うことで、悪運が好運を上回ったこと(または他人の好運があなた自身のそれを上回ったこと)を強調します。foo "
"indexとcoefficient of "
"fooはどちらも、fooが厳密に測定可能ではないにせよ、少なくとも大きくも小さくもなりうるものであることを含意する傾向があります。したがって、ある論文や人物について高いbogosity"
" index(ボーガス度指数)を持つと言うかもしれませんが、高いbogosity factorとはあまり言わないでしょう。foo "
"indexは、ありふれた生計費指数のように、fooが多くの量の凝縮であることを示唆します。coefficient of "
"fooは、摩擦係数のように、fooが基本的な量であることを示唆します。これらの用語の選択はしばしば個人の好みの問題です。たとえば、bogosityが基本的な属性だと感じる人はcoefficient"
" of bogosityと言い、それが諸因子の組み合わせだと感じる人はbogosity indexと言うかもしれません。"
